{{fr-noun|m}}

# a [[river]] that flows into an [[ocean]] or [[sea]] (a river that flows into another river or body of water is called a {{m|fr|rivière}})
#: {{ux|fr|L’Amazone est un '''fleuve''' d'Amérique du Sud.|t=The Amazon is a '''river''' located in South America.}}
#: {{ux|fr|Le '''fleuve''' Churchill au Labrador se jette dans l'Atlantique, alors que la rivière Churchill au Manitoba se jette dans la baie d'Hudson.|t=The Churchill '''River''' in Labrador flows into the Atlantic Ocean, whereas the Churchill River in Manitoba flows into Hudson Bay.}}
# {{lb|fr|figurative}} a continuous and unstoppable stream of people, things, or words
#: {{ux|fr|Ce qui devait être une brève question est rapidement devenue un discours-'''fleuve'''.|t=What was supposed to be a brief question quickly became a '''long-winded''' speech.}}
#* {{quote-text|fr|year=1900|author=w:Paul Margueritte; w:Victor Margueritte|title=Les Tronçons du glaive
|passage=Tandis que le lugubre '''fleuve''' d'hommes, sinuant à travers les routes encaissées, précipitait vers Pontarlier le débordement de ses vagues, […].|t=As the grim '''river''' of people, winding through the steep-walled roads, sent its overflowing waves toward Pontarlier...}}
# {{lb|fr|mythology|art}} a river god, or the allegorical artistic representation of a river as an old, bearded man lying on reeds and holding or leaning on an urn from which the river's water flows
#* {{quote-text|fr|year=1842|author=w:Jean Louis Armand de Quatrefages de Bréau|chapter=L’Archipel de Chausey, souvenirs d’un Naturaliste,|title=Revue des Deux Mondes|volume=30
|passage=Les îles grandissent peu à peu et s'entourent d'une large ceinture de roches tapissées de mousses noirâtres ou de longs fucus bruns qui pendent à leurs flancs comme les roseaux de marbre dont les sculpteurs du dernier siècle ornaient leurs statues de '''fleuves'''.|t=The islands gradually grow and are surrounded by a broad belt of rocks carpeted with blackish mosses or long brown seaweed hanging from their sides, like the marble reeds with which last century's sculptors decorated their statues of '''river gods'''.}}

